window.MODULES=window.MODULES||{};window.MODULES["hemodynamics"]={"slug": "hemodynamics", "title": "Invasive Hemodynamics", "tagline": "Right-heart catheterization from waveform to bedside decision — pressures, output, resistance, shunts, shock profiles, and the constriction-restriction-tamponade problem.", "level": 3, "readMin": 45, "takeaways": ["Every RHC number is only as good as your zeroing (mid-thorax, phlebostatic axis) and your habit of reading pressures at END-EXPIRATION, when intrathoracic pressure is closest to atmospheric.", "Master the a/c/v waves and x/y descents: a cannon a wave means AV dissociation, a giant v wave means MR or a non-compliant LA, a steep-then-plateaued y descent means constriction, and a blunted y descent means tamponade.", "Fick output is most reliable at low output and thermodilution is unreliable in severe TR, low output, and intracardiac shunts — pick the method to match the physiology in front of you.", "Constriction, restriction, and tamponade all raise and equalize diastolic pressures; you separate them with the y descent, Kussmaul sign, respiratory RV-LV systolic DISCORDANCE (ventricular interdependence), and the dissociation of intrathoracic from intracardiac pressure.", "Convert numbers to a shock phenotype (wet/dry, warm/cold; SCAI stage) before you reach for a drug — the hemodynamic profile, not the label, chooses the vasopressor, inotrope, or vasodilator."], "sections": [{"id": "overview", "title": "Why and When to Measure Pressures Directly", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "Invasive hemodynamics is the direct, catheter-based measurement of intracardiac and intravascular pressures, flows, and resistances. Echocardiography estimates most of these noninvasively, so a right-heart catheterization (RHC) earns its place only when a specific number will change management: confirming and phenotyping pulmonary hypertension, distinguishing pre- from post-capillary disease, quantifying a shunt, defining the physiology of cardiogenic or mixed shock, or resolving constriction versus restriction versus tamponade when imaging is equivocal."}, {"type": "figure", "src": "../assets/fig/swan-ganz.jpg", "alt": "Pulmonary artery (Swan-Ganz) catheter", "caption": "The pulmonary artery (Swan-Ganz) catheter and its course through the right heart.", "credit": "Tariq Abdulla et al. — CC BY-SA 3.0, Wikimedia Commons", "source": "https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Pulmonary_artery_catheter_english.JPG"}, {"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "The core toolkit is a balloon-tipped, flow-directed pulmonary artery catheter (Swan-Ganz), a pressure transducer referenced to the correct zero, and a disciplined habit of reading every value at end-expiration. Everything downstream — cardiac output, resistances, shunt fractions, valve areas — is arithmetic built on those raw pressures and a measured flow."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 2, "label": "Fellow-level framing", "text": "Do not order an RHC to \"get numbers.\" Write the clinical question first (\"Is this precapillary PH?\", \"Is the wedge really elevated or am I over-wedging?\", \"Is the shock cardiogenic or distributive?\"), then design the run — pressures, a full oximetry set if a shunt is possible, a Fick and a thermodilution output, and provocation (fluid, exercise, or vasodilator) if the resting study may be falsely normal."}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 2, "label": "Vocabulary you will use all day", "entries": [{"term": "RHC", "def": "Right-heart catheterization — RA, RV, PA, and pulmonary capillary wedge pressures plus cardiac output via a PA catheter."}, {"term": "PCWP / PAWP", "def": "Pulmonary capillary wedge (arterial occlusion) pressure — a downstream surrogate for left atrial pressure and, in mid-diastole, for LVEDP."}, {"term": "LVEDP", "def": "Left ventricular end-diastolic pressure — measured directly at left-heart catheterization, the reference standard for left-sided filling pressure."}, {"term": "TPG / DPG", "def": "Transpulmonary gradient (mPAP − PCWP) and diastolic pulmonary gradient (PA diastolic − PCWP) — used to characterize the pulmonary vascular bed."}, {"term": "Qp/Qs", "def": "Ratio of pulmonary to systemic blood flow — the shunt fraction derived from an oximetry run."}]}, {"type": "linkout", "depth": 1, "text": "Orient to the hardware before you read a tracing: study a labeled Swan-Ganz / pulmonary artery catheter diagram (lumens, balloon, thermistor, and the RA→RV→PA→wedge course) alongside the intracardiac anatomy it traverses.", "url": "https://radiopaedia.org", "label": "Radiopaedia — Swan-Ganz / PA catheter and cardiac anatomy"}]}, {"id": "catheter", "title": "The Swan-Ganz Catheter: Anatomy, Course, and Setup", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "The standard 7–7.5 Fr thermodilution PA catheter is roughly 110 cm long with 10 cm markings. It carries a distal (PA) lumen, a proximal (RA) lumen ~30 cm back, a balloon just proximal to the tip (inflated with up to 1.5 mL of air), and a thermistor ~4 cm from the tip for thermodilution output. Advanced from a central vein, the balloon is inflated once the tip is central and the catheter is flow-directed through RA → RV → PA → wedge, each transition announced by a characteristic waveform change."}, {"type": "steps", "depth": 1, "label": "Insertion and float sequence", "items": ["Zero and level the transducer at the phlebostatic axis (mid-thorax, 4th intercostal space at the mid-axillary line) with the patient supine.", "Advance to a central position (~15–20 cm from an internal jugular/subclavian site), confirm a low RA waveform, then INFLATE the balloon.", "Float through the tricuspid valve: the tracing gains a wide pulse pressure with a rapid systolic upstroke and a diastolic pressure that DIPS toward zero — the RV.", "Cross the pulmonic valve into the PA: the diastolic pressure RISES and a dicrotic notch appears; PA systolic equals RV systolic in the absence of RVOT obstruction.", "Advance until the tracing damps to a wedge with a and v waves — that is the occlusion (wedge) position; then DEFLATE the balloon and confirm the PA tracing returns.", "Always inflate to advance and deflate to withdraw; wedge with the minimum balloon volume that gives a clean tracing."]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 1, "label": "Danger", "text": "If a good wedge waveform appears with <1.25 mL of balloon inflation, or the tracing looks continuously \"wedged\" with the balloon down, the tip is too distal — advancing or inflating risks PA rupture, the most feared complication. Pull back until a full PA tracing returns. Never flush a permanently wedged catheter."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 1, "label": "Mnemonic", "text": "Chamber order on the float — \"Right Room, Right Ventricle, Perfect Ascent, Wedge\": RA → RV → PA → Wedge. The two things that go UP as you cross a valve are the RV systolic (tricuspid) and the PA diastolic (pulmonic); the diastolic that DIPS toward zero tells you the tip is still in the RV."}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "label": "Waveform signature at each transition", "head": ["Location", "Systolic", "Diastolic", "Signature clue"], "rows": [["RA", "—", "2–6 (mean)", "a, c, v waves; x and y descents"], ["RV", "15–30", "2–8 (early), rises to EDP", "Diastolic DIPS to near zero; wide pulse pressure"], ["PA", "15–30", "8–15", "Diastolic RISES; dicrotic notch appears"], ["PCWP", "—", "6–12 (mean)", "Damped; a and v waves; phase-lagged behind ECG"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "label": "Fellowship nuance — when the float is hard", "text": "A dilated RA/RV, severe TR, or low output makes the catheter coil rather than advance. Tricks: turn the patient to the left lateral position, have them take a deep breath to increase venous return, inject 10 mL of iced saline to stiffen the catheter transiently, or use fluoroscopy. In severe TR, thermodilution output is unreliable regardless of how cleanly you wedge — plan a Fick output before you start."}]}, {"id": "waveforms", "title": "Reading the Atrial and Ventricular Waveforms", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "The right (and left) atrial pressure tracing has three positive waves and two descents, each tied to a mechanical event. Mastering them turns a squiggle into a diagnosis. The a wave is atrial contraction (follows the P wave), the c wave is tricuspid/mitral valve closure bulging into the atrium (follows the QRS), and the v wave is passive atrial filling against a closed AV valve during ventricular systole (near the T wave). The x descent is atrial relaxation and downward pull of the base during systole; the y descent is rapid atrial emptying when the AV valve opens."}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 1, "label": "The atrial waveform, component by component", "entries": [{"term": "a wave", "def": "Atrial systole. Absent in atrial fibrillation; giant/cannon a waves when the atrium contracts against a closed AV valve (AV dissociation, tricuspid stenosis, RV hypertrophy)."}, {"term": "c wave", "def": "AV valve closure — a small notch on the a-wave downslope. Not always visible."}, {"term": "v wave", "def": "Atrial filling during ventricular systole. Giant v waves = severe mitral (on wedge) or tricuspid (on RA) regurgitation, or a stiff/non-compliant atrium."}, {"term": "x descent", "def": "Atrial relaxation. Prominent in tamponade (dominant x)."}, {"term": "y descent", "def": "Early diastolic atrial emptying. Steep and deep in constriction; BLUNTED or absent in tamponade."}]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 1, "label": "Mnemonic", "text": "Timing the waves to the ECG — \"a before, c during, v after\": the a wave sits just after the P wave, the c wave rides the QRS, and the v wave peaks around the T wave. For the descents, remember \"x before y, systole then diastole\" — x falls during systole, y falls in early diastole when the valve opens."}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "label": "Pathologic waveform patterns and what they mean", "head": ["Finding", "Where", "Mechanism / diagnosis"], "rows": [["Cannon a waves", "RA", "Atrium contracts against closed tricuspid — complete heart block, VT, junctional rhythm, PVCs"], ["Large a wave, no v", "RA/wedge", "Tricuspid/mitral stenosis, non-compliant ventricle"], ["Absent a wave", "RA/wedge", "Atrial fibrillation"], ["Giant v wave", "Wedge", "Severe mitral regurgitation or stiff LA — can be mistaken for a PA tracing"], ["Giant v wave / \"ventricularized\" RA", "RA", "Severe tricuspid regurgitation"], ["Prominent x, blunted y", "RA", "Cardiac tamponade"], ["Prominent x AND y (M/W pattern)", "RA", "Constrictive pericarditis"], ["Steep y descent alone", "RA", "Severe TR, restrictive cardiomyopathy"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "label": "Fellowship pitfall — the v wave that fools you", "text": "A giant wedge v wave can be transmitted into the PA tracing and make a wedged catheter look un-wedged (a \"c-v\" wave on PA that peaks AFTER the T wave, later than the true PA systolic peak which precedes the T wave). Confirm the wedge by timing (wedge waves lag the ECG relative to PA), by oxygen saturation (a true wedge sample is arterialized, >95%), and by the mean pressure being lower than PA diastolic. Read the mean wedge, not the peak of the v wave, when calculating a mitral gradient or PVR."}, {"type": "linkout", "depth": 1, "text": "To build pattern recognition for labeled RA, RV, PA, and wedge tracings — the a/c/v waves, x/y descents, and the RV-to-PA transition — a curated waveform library annotated to the ECG is the fastest study aid.", "url": "https://litfl.com/ecg-library", "label": "LITFL — invasive pressure and ECG waveform library"}]}, {"id": "normal-values", "title": "Normal Pressures, Zeroing, and Leveling", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "A pressure is meaningless without a correct reference. Zero the transducer to atmosphere and LEVEL it to the phlebostatic axis (mid-thoracic, roughly the mid-axillary line at the 4th intercostal space, approximating the level of the RA/LA). A transducer set too low reads falsely high; too high reads falsely low — about 0.75 mmHg per cm of vertical error. Re-zero when the patient's position changes."}, {"type": "table", "depth": 1, "label": "Normal resting hemodynamic values", "head": ["Parameter", "Normal range", "Units"], "rows": [["RA (mean)", "2–6", "mmHg"], ["RV", "15–30 / 2–8", "mmHg (sys/EDP)"], ["PA", "15–30 / 8–15 (mean 10–18)", "mmHg"], ["PCWP (mean)", "6–12", "mmHg"], ["LV", "90–140 / 6–12", "mmHg (sys/EDP)"], ["Aorta", "90–140 / 60–90 (mean 70–105)", "mmHg"], ["Cardiac output / index", "4–8 / 2.5–4.0", "L/min ; L/min/m²"], ["SVR", "800–1200", "dynes·s·cm⁻⁵"], ["PVR", "<2 (approx <160 dynes)", "Wood units"], ["Mixed venous O₂ sat (SvO₂)", "60–80", "%"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 1, "label": "Pearl", "text": "READ EVERYTHING AT END-EXPIRATION. At end-expiration intrathoracic pressure is closest to atmospheric, so the intracardiac pressure you measure is truest. On the tracing, end-expiration is the pressure PEAK during spontaneous breathing (inspiration pulls pressures down) and the pressure NADIR during positive-pressure ventilation (inspiration pushes pressures up). Do not trust the machine's auto-mean — trace it yourself."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 2, "label": "Fellow-level", "text": "PA diastolic pressure normally approximates mean PCWP (within ~1–4 mmHg) because there is no gradient across the pulmonary bed in diastole. When PAd markedly exceeds wedge, suspect precapillary pulmonary vascular disease (an elevated diastolic pulmonary gradient). This relationship also lets you trend left-sided filling from a continuous PAd when you cannot wedge repeatedly."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 2, "label": "Danger — the over-wedge and under-wedge traps", "text": "A falsely HIGH wedge (over-wedging) comes from an over-inflated balloon or a too-distal tip forcing pressure up — the tracing drifts upward and loses crisp a/v waves. A falsely LOW wedge (partial wedge) under-reads left filling. Confirm a true wedge with an arterialized O₂ saturation and clean phase-lagged a/v waves before you commit to a low number in a dyspneic patient — a spuriously low wedge can send you down the wrong (precapillary) pathway."}]}, {"id": "cardiac-output", "title": "Cardiac Output: Fick versus Thermodilution", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "Two independent methods, each with a domain where it lies to you. The Fick principle computes output from oxygen uptake and the arteriovenous O₂ difference; thermodilution computes it from the decay curve of injected cold saline sensed at the PA thermistor. Whenever the numbers matter — pulmonary vascular resistance, shunt fractions, valve areas — obtain both and reconcile them."}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 1, "label": "The two output methods", "entries": [{"term": "Fick output", "def": "CO (L/min) = VO₂ / [(SaO₂ − SvO₂) × Hb × 13.4]. VO₂ is oxygen consumption (measured, or estimated as ~125 mL/min/m²). Most accurate in LOW-output states."}, {"term": "Assumed vs measured Fick", "def": "Estimating VO₂ introduces error, especially in the obese, elderly, septic, and critically ill; a measured VO₂ is the reference standard when precision is required."}, {"term": "Thermodilution", "def": "Cold saline injected in the RA, temperature change integrated at the PA thermistor (area under the curve is inversely proportional to flow). Average 3 concordant injections. Most accurate at NORMAL/HIGH output."}]}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "label": "Choosing (and distrusting) the method", "head": ["Scenario", "Preferred", "Why the other fails"], "rows": [["Low cardiac output", "Fick", "Thermodilution overestimates at low flow (slow, prolonged curve, more thermal loss)"], ["Severe tricuspid regurgitation", "Fick", "Regurgitant recirculation distorts the thermodilution curve → unreliable"], ["Intracardiac shunt", "Fick / oximetry", "Thermodilution invalid — recirculating indicator; use oximetric Qp/Qs"], ["Normal/high output, no TR/shunt", "Thermodilution", "Assumed-VO₂ Fick error grows; thermodilution is quick and reproducible"], ["Arrhythmia (AF, frequent PVCs)", "Average many measurements", "Beat-to-beat variability degrades both; more injections needed"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 1, "label": "Pearl", "text": "SvO₂ is a free, continuous cardiac-output surrogate. A mixed venous saturation from the PA falling below ~60% (or a widening A-V O₂ difference) signals that tissue extraction is rising to defend delivery — usually a falling output. A high SvO₂ (>80%) suggests a left-to-right shunt, high-output states, impaired extraction (sepsis, cyanide), or a wedged sampling error."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "label": "Fellowship arithmetic", "text": "The 13.4 constant = 1.34 mL O₂/g Hb × 10 (to reconcile g/dL with L). Some use 1.36 (from 13.6). Oxygen CONTENT of a compartment = 1.34 × Hb × sat + 0.003 × PO₂; the dissolved term is negligible except on 100% FiO₂ during shunt runs, where you must add it. Index everything to BSA before you compare a patient to normals or to their prior study."}]}, {"id": "resistance", "title": "Vascular Resistance and the Pulmonary Gradients", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "Resistance is the pressure drop across a bed divided by the flow through it. These derived numbers drive decisions in pulmonary hypertension, heart-transplant candidacy, and shock. Keep resistances in Wood units when you think about the pulmonary bed (multiply by 80 for dynes·s·cm⁻⁵) because the transplant and PH thresholds are quoted in Wood units."}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 1, "label": "Resistance and gradient formulas", "entries": [{"term": "PVR (Wood units)", "def": "(mPAP − PCWP) / cardiac output. Normal <2 WU. Elevated PVR defines the pulmonary vascular contribution to PH."}, {"term": "SVR (dynes·s·cm⁻⁵)", "def": "80 × (mean arterial pressure − mean RA) / cardiac output. Normal ~800–1200. Low in distributive/septic shock, high in cardiogenic shock."}, {"term": "TPG", "def": "Transpulmonary gradient = mPAP − mean PCWP. >12 mmHg suggests a pulmonary vascular component, but is flow- and volume-sensitive."}, {"term": "DPG", "def": "Diastolic pulmonary gradient = PA diastolic − mean PCWP. Less flow-dependent than TPG; historically ≥7 mmHg flagged combined pre/post-capillary PH, though it is no longer part of the formal definition."}]}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "label": "Hemodynamic definition of pulmonary hypertension (ESC/ERS 2022)", "head": ["Category", "mPAP", "PCWP", "PVR"], "rows": [["Pulmonary hypertension (any)", "> 20 mmHg", "—", "—"], ["Pre-capillary PH", "> 20", "≤ 15", "> 2 WU"], ["Isolated post-capillary (IpcPH)", "> 20", "> 15", "≤ 2 WU"], ["Combined pre/post-capillary (CpcPH)", "> 20", "> 15", "> 2 WU"], ["Exercise PH", "mPAP/CO slope > 3 mmHg/L/min", "—", "—"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 2, "label": "Fellow-level — the 2022 threshold shift", "text": "The ESC/ERS 2022 guideline LOWERED the mPAP cutoff for PH from ≥25 to >20 mmHg and set the PVR threshold at >2 WU (previously ≥3). The old \"25/15/3\" is out of date. This matters most for the large group with mildly elevated PVR (2–3 WU) who now meet a hemodynamic definition — interpret them in clinical context, not in isolation."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 1, "label": "Pearl", "text": "Before you call PVR elevated, sanity-check the wedge and the output. An over-wedged (falsely high) PCWP shrinks the calculated TPG and hides precapillary disease; a low measured output inflates PVR. Garbage pressures in, garbage resistance out — always confirm a clean, arterialized wedge and a reconciled cardiac output first."}]}, {"id": "shunts", "title": "The Oximetry Run and Shunt Quantification", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "When an intracardiac shunt is possible — unexplained right-heart enlargement, a step-up in saturation, high SvO₂, or paradoxical embolism — perform a saturation run: sample O₂ saturation sequentially from SVC, IVC, RA (high/mid/low), RV (inflow/mid/outflow), PA, and the systemic artery. A significant \"step-up\" localizes a left-to-right shunt to the chamber where oxygenated blood is entering."}, {"type": "table", "depth": 1, "label": "Diagnostic oxygen saturation step-up", "head": ["Level of step-up", "Threshold (Δ sat)", "Lesion"], "rows": [["SVC/IVC → RA", "≥ 7%", "ASD, anomalous pulmonary venous return, VSD with TR, ruptured sinus of Valsalva"], ["RA → RV", "≥ 5%", "VSD, primum ASD, ruptured sinus of Valsalva into RV"], ["RV → PA", "≥ 5%", "PDA, aortopulmonary window"]]}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 2, "label": "Shunt calculations", "entries": [{"term": "Mixed venous (for Qp/Qs)", "def": "Flamm formula = (3 × SVC sat + 1 × IVC sat) / 4, used as the systemic venous input when a step-up prevents using PA saturation as mixed venous."}, {"term": "Qp/Qs", "def": "(SaO₂ − SvO₂) / (SpvO₂ − SpaO₂). Pulmonary venous sat is assumed 95–98% if not measured. Ratio 1 = no shunt."}, {"term": "Interpretation", "def": "Qp/Qs > 1 = net left-to-right; < 1 = net right-to-left. A ratio ≥ 1.5–2.0 is the classic threshold at which ASD/VSD closure is considered (with clinical/imaging context)."}]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 1, "label": "Mnemonic", "text": "Step-up magnitude by level — \"7-5-5, top to bottom\": ≥7% to open an atrial step-up (great veins → RA), ≥5% for ventricular (RA → RV), ≥5% for great-vessel (RV → PA). The atrium needs a bigger step-up because SVC and IVC saturations differ widely at baseline, so the noise floor is higher."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "label": "Fellowship caveat", "text": "Thermodilution output is INVALID in the presence of a shunt (recirculating indicator), so Qp and Qs must both come from the oximetric Fick method. Sample quickly and in a fixed order to minimize drift, and draw the systemic (pulmonary venous surrogate) sample on the same FiO₂. If the patient is on supplemental O₂, add the dissolved-oxygen term or the step-up can be masked."}]}, {"id": "wedge", "title": "Wedge Pressure, LVEDP, and the Left Atrium", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "The wedge is the workhorse and the trap. Occluding a PA branch creates a static column of blood continuous with the pulmonary veins and left atrium, so mean PCWP estimates mean LA pressure, and the wedge a-wave nadir in mid-diastole approximates LVEDP when the mitral valve is normal. The wedge is phase-LAGGED behind the true LA pressure because it is transmitted retrograde through the lung — always correlate wedge waves to the ECG with that delay in mind."}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "label": "When PCWP and LVEDP diverge", "head": ["Situation", "Effect", "Consequence"], "rows": [["Severe mitral regurgitation", "Giant v wave; mean wedge overestimates LVEDP", "Use the pre-a (mid-diastolic) point, not the v-wave peak"], ["Mitral stenosis", "Wedge > LVEDP by the transmitral gradient", "The gradient IS the pathology — measure it"], ["Stiff, non-compliant LV / HFpEF", "LVEDP may exceed mean wedge", "Resting wedge can be falsely reassuring — provoke"], ["Pulmonary veno-occlusive disease", "Wedge underestimates true capillary pressure", "Precapillary numbers with pulmonary edema — beware"], ["Tachycardia", "a wave merges, mid-diastolic point lost", "Slow the heart or read LVEDP directly"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 2, "label": "Fellow-level — provocation for occult HFpEF", "text": "A resting wedge <15 mmHg does not exclude HFpEF in a dyspneic patient. Exercise the patient supine on the table: a PCWP rising to ≥25 mmHg with exercise (or an mPAP/CO slope >3) unmasks post-capillary disease. A rapid saline challenge (e.g., 500 mL) driving wedge to ≥18 mmHg is an alternative provocation when exercise is not feasible."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 1, "label": "Pearl", "text": "When wedge and clinical picture disagree, go to the source: cross the aortic valve and measure LVEDP directly. Simultaneous LV and PCWP tracings settle the mitral-stenosis, giant-v-wave, and over-wedge questions in one shot — the two mean diastolic pressures should superimpose when the mitral valve and the wedge are both honest."}]}, {"id": "valvular", "title": "Valve Gradients and the Gorlin Equation", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "Invasive valve assessment pairs a pressure gradient across the valve with a flow to solve for an area. For aortic stenosis, record simultaneous LV and aortic pressures (a dual-lumen pigtail or two catheters); for mitral stenosis, use simultaneous LV and PCWP (or transseptal LA). The peak-to-peak gradient (invasive) is not the same as the echo peak-instantaneous gradient — the invasive mean gradient is the number that maps to echo and to guideline thresholds."}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 2, "label": "Valve-area formulas", "entries": [{"term": "Gorlin (AS)", "def": "Valve area = CO / (SEP × HR × 44.3 × √mean gradient). SEP = systolic ejection period. 44.3 is the empiric aortic constant."}, {"term": "Gorlin (MS)", "def": "Same form but flow is divided by the DIASTOLIC filling period and the constant is 37.7 (some use 38)."}, {"term": "Hakki simplification", "def": "Valve area ≈ CO / √(peak gradient). A fast bedside approximation; least reliable at extremes of heart rate."}]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 2, "label": "Danger — low-flow, low-gradient AS", "text": "Gorlin-derived area is FLOW-DEPENDENT: at low cardiac output the calculated area shrinks even when the valve is not truly critical (pseudo-severe AS). In low-flow/low-gradient AS, dobutamine challenge in the cath lab (or by echo) separates true-severe (fixed area, rising gradient) from pseudo-severe (area increases with flow). Never call severity off a Gorlin area computed on a low output without confirming flow reserve."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 1, "label": "Pearl", "text": "In aortic stenosis, do NOT use the femoral-sheath pressure as \"aortic\" without correcting: peripheral amplification and sheath damping distort the gradient. Pull the pigtail back across the valve for a true LV-to-aortic gradient, or use a dual-lumen catheter for a simultaneous, co-located measurement. A negligible pullback gradient in a patient echo calls severe should make you re-check catheter position, not the echo."}, {"type": "linkout", "depth": 1, "text": "For the original description and derivation of the hydraulic valve-area equation used at catheterization, the primary hemodynamic literature is the definitive source.", "url": "https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov", "label": "PubMed — Gorlin and Gorlin, valve area formula"}]}, {"id": "shock", "title": "Hemodynamic Profiles of Shock and Tailored Therapy", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "The RHC earns its keep in undifferentiated or mixed shock. Convert the raw numbers into a phenotype: filling pressure (wet vs dry, by wedge), perfusion (warm vs cold, by cardiac index and SVR), and trajectory (SCAI stage). The phenotype — not the diagnostic label — chooses the drug and the device."}, {"type": "table", "depth": 1, "label": "Forrester / Stevenson profiles (left-heart filling × perfusion)", "head": ["Profile", "Congestion (wedge)", "Perfusion (CI)", "Approach"], "rows": [["Warm & dry (A)", "Normal (<18)", "Adequate (>2.2)", "Compensated — no acute vasoactives"], ["Warm & wet (B)", "High (>18)", "Adequate", "Diuresis ± vasodilator (nitroglycerin/nitroprusside)"], ["Cold & dry (L)", "Low/normal", "Low (<2.2)", "Cautious volume; inotrope if still hypoperfused"], ["Cold & wet (C)", "High", "Low", "Inotrope + diuresis; escalate to MCS if refractory"]]}, {"type": "table", "depth": 1, "label": "Shock by resistance and output", "head": ["Type", "CO/CI", "SVR", "PCWP", "SvO₂"], "rows": [["Cardiogenic", "Low", "High", "High", "Low"], ["Hypovolemic", "Low", "High", "Low", "Low"], ["Distributive (septic)", "High (or normal)", "Low", "Low/normal", "High"], ["Obstructive (PE/tamponade)", "Low", "High", "Varies (equalized in tamponade)", "Low"]]}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "label": "Vasoactive agents in cardiogenic and mixed shock", "head": ["Drug | Class / mechanism", "Start dose", "Usual / target", "Key contraindication", "Major adverse effects", "Monitoring"], "rows": [["Norepinephrine | α1 > β1 vasopressor", "0.05 mcg/kg/min", "0.05–0.5 (up to ~1) mcg/kg/min", "Uncorrected hypovolemia", "Arrhythmia, digital/limb ischemia, extravasation necrosis", "Arterial line MAP, rhythm, lactate, urine output"], ["Dobutamine | β1 inotrope (β2 vasodilation)", "2.5 mcg/kg/min", "2.5–10 (max ~20) mcg/kg/min", "Dynamic LVOT obstruction, severe tachyarrhythmia", "Hypotension, tachycardia, arrhythmia, myocardial O₂ demand", "Rhythm, BP, CI/SvO₂ trend"], ["Milrinone | PDE-3 inhibitor inodilator", "no bolus (avoid) or 25–50 mcg/kg", "0.125–0.5 mcg/kg/min", "Severe hypotension; renal failure (accumulates)", "Hypotension, ventricular arrhythmia, thrombocytopenia", "BP, rhythm; renally dose-adjust"], ["Dopamine | dose-dependent DA/β/α", "2–5 mcg/kg/min", "5–20 mcg/kg/min", "Pheochromocytoma, tachyarrhythmia", "More arrhythmia than norepi (esp. cardiogenic shock)", "Rhythm, BP; not first-line in shock"], ["Vasopressin | V1 vasoconstrictor", "0.03 units/min (fixed)", "0.03–0.04 units/min", "—", "Splanchnic/digital ischemia, hyponatremia", "MAP, perfusion; adjunct to norepi"], ["Nitroprusside | NO arterial+venous vasodilator", "0.3 mcg/kg/min", "0.3–5 (max ~10) mcg/kg/min", "Hypotension, high ICP, hepatic/renal failure", "Cyanide/thiocyanate toxicity, coronary steal, reflex tachycardia", "Continuous arterial BP; limit duration/dose"], ["Nitroglycerin | NO venodilator (arterial at high dose)", "5–10 mcg/min", "titrate to 20–200 mcg/min", "RV infarction/preload dependence, PDE-5 inhibitor use", "Headache, hypotension, tachyphylaxis", "BP, symptoms"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 2, "label": "Danger", "text": "In cardiogenic shock, dopamine causes more arrhythmias and, in the SOAP II trial, more death in the cardiogenic subgroup than norepinephrine — norepinephrine is the preferred first-line pressor. Never load a milrinone bolus in a hypotensive shock patient; its long half-life makes hypotension hard to reverse. Nitroprusside beyond 24–48 h or in renal failure risks cyanide accumulation — monitor and cap the dose."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "label": "Fellowship framing — SCAI SHOCK stages", "text": "Stage the patient A (at risk) → B (beginning, hypotension/tachycardia without hypoperfusion) → C (classic, hypoperfusion needing pharmacologic/mechanical support) → D (deteriorating despite initial support) → E (extremis, refractory). Rising lactate and a falling cardiac power output (CPO = MAP × CO / 451; <0.6 W predicts mortality) and a low PAPi (PA pulsatility index = [PAsys − PAdia] / RA; a low value, commonly <1.0, flags RV failure) drive escalation to mechanical support. These two derived indices are the fellow's shorthand for LV and RV adequacy."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 1, "label": "Pearl", "text": "The ESCAPE trial showed routine PA-catheter guidance did not improve outcomes in decompensated heart failure — so the RHC is not a monitor to place reflexively. Its value is diagnostic and in the patient whose physiology is genuinely unclear or refractory. Place it to answer a question, pull it once the question is answered."}]}, {"id": "constriction-restriction-tamponade", "title": "Constriction vs Restriction vs Tamponade", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "This is the highest-yield hemodynamic discrimination in the cath lab, and it turns on a shared final common pathway: all three raise and tend to equalize diastolic filling pressures. You separate them by the SHAPE of the descents, the RESPONSE to respiration, and — the deepest concept — whether intrathoracic pressure changes are transmitted to the cardiac chambers."}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 1, "label": "The three physiologies in one line each", "entries": [{"term": "Constrictive pericarditis", "def": "A rigid, non-compliant pericardial shell. Early filling is unimpeded then abruptly halted (dip-and-plateau); the heart is DISSOCIATED from intrathoracic pressure swings, driving ventricular interdependence."}, {"term": "Restrictive cardiomyopathy", "def": "A stiff MYOCARDIUM (amyloid, sarcoid, fibrosis). Filling pressures are high and left often exceeds right; the pericardium is normal, so intrathoracic-intracardiac coupling is preserved."}, {"term": "Cardiac tamponade", "def": "Pericardial fluid under pressure compresses all chambers throughout diastole. Filling is impaired from the START of diastole — the y descent is blunted/lost."}]}, {"type": "table", "depth": 1, "label": "Head-to-head hemodynamic comparison", "head": ["Feature", "Constriction", "Restriction", "Tamponade"], "rows": [["Diastolic pressure equalization (within ~5 mmHg)", "Yes (RA=RV EDP=PCWP=LVEDP)", "No — LVEDP usually > RVEDP by >5", "Yes — all diastolic pressures equalized"], ["RA waveform", "Prominent x AND y (M/W pattern)", "Prominent y, steep", "Prominent x, BLUNTED/absent y"], ["Ventricular tracing", "Dip-and-plateau (square-root sign)", "Dip-and-plateau may be present", "No dip-and-plateau; monophasic"], ["Kussmaul sign (RA fails to fall/rises on inspiration)", "Present", "May be present", "Absent (classically)"], ["Pulsus paradoxus (>10 mmHg SBP fall on inspiration)", "Usually absent", "Absent", "Present (hallmark)"], ["RV-LV systolic peaks with respiration", "DISCORDANT (interdependence)", "CONCORDANT", "Concordant (both fall on inspiration)"], ["Intrathoracic–intracardiac pressure coupling", "DISSOCIATED (shielded by rigid shell)", "Preserved (coupled)", "Preserved"], ["RVEDP / RV systolic ratio", "> 1/3", "Variable", "—"], ["PA systolic pressure", "Usually < 55 mmHg", "Often > 55 mmHg", "Low/normal"], ["Respiratory PCWP–LV filling gradient", "Dissociation present (gradient falls with inspiration)", "Absent", "—"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "label": "The two deepest fellowship concepts", "text": "(1) DISSOCIATION OF INTRATHORACIC AND INTRACARDIAC PRESSURES: in a normal or restrictive heart, inspiration lowers intrathoracic pressure and that drop is transmitted to the pulmonary veins AND the LV, so the driving gradient for LV filling is unchanged. In CONSTRICTION the rigid shell shields the chambers — inspiration lowers pulmonary-vein/PCWP pressure but NOT LV diastolic pressure, so the transmitral driving gradient falls with inspiration (the PCWP–LV pressure gradient diverges). (2) VENTRICULAR INTERDEPENDENCE: with a fixed total cardiac volume, inspiratory augmentation of RV filling bows the septum leftward and reduces LV filling, so RV systolic pressure RISES while LV systolic pressure FALLS on inspiration — DISCORDANT peaks. In restriction the ventricles are not coupled by a rigid shell and their systolic pressures move CONCORDANTLY (both fall with inspiration). This respiratory systolic DISCORDANCE (quantified as the systolic area index >1.1) is the single most specific invasive sign of constriction."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 1, "label": "Mnemonic", "text": "Descents — \"tamponade = X only, constriction = both (W)\": tamponade blunts the y (the ventricle never gets an unimpeded early-filling phase), so the x dominates; constriction preserves rapid early filling then slams shut, giving BOTH a steep x and a steep y — an M or W-shaped atrial tracing. And \"Kussmaul & discordance say the pericardium is the problem; concordance says the muscle is.\""}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 2, "label": "Danger — the great mimic", "text": "Constriction and restriction can coexist and both cause the dip-and-plateau. A single tracing feature is not enough — the DISCRIMINATOR is dynamic respiratory RV-LV systolic discordance recorded on simultaneous high-fidelity RV and LV tracings. If you rely on static equalization alone you will misclassify the restrictive-cardiomyopathy patient (in whom LVEDP exceeds RVEDP and pericardiectomy would be harmful)."}, {"type": "p", "depth": 2, "text": "Cross-reference the pericardial-disease module for the imaging counterparts — septal bounce, respirophasic septal shift, and dilated IVC on echo/CT/MRI mirror these catheter findings, and the two together secure the diagnosis before committing a patient to pericardiectomy."}, {"type": "linkout", "depth": 1, "text": "For labeled invasive tracings of the dip-and-plateau (square-root sign), the M/W atrial pattern, and respiratory RV-LV discordance, a curated hemodynamics and waveform library is the best study aid.", "url": "https://litfl.com/ecg-library", "label": "LITFL — constriction vs restriction vs tamponade tracings"}]}, {"id": "tamponade", "title": "Tamponade Physiology and Pericardiocentesis Hemodynamics", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "Tamponade is a continuum, not a threshold: what matters is the RATE of accumulation against pericardial compliance, not the absolute volume. A rapidly accumulating 150 mL can tamponade; a slow chronic effusion can hold a liter. The defining physiology is exaggerated ventricular interdependence with equalized, elevated intrapericardial and diastolic chamber pressures throughout diastole."}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 1, "label": "The clinical-hemodynamic signature", "entries": [{"term": "Pulsus paradoxus", "def": "An inspiratory fall in systolic BP >10 mmHg. Inspiration augments RV filling; with a fixed pericardial volume the septum bows into the LV, dropping stroke volume and systemic pressure."}, {"term": "Blunted y descent", "def": "The pericardial pressure prevents rapid early ventricular filling, so the atrial y descent is attenuated — distinguishing tamponade from constriction (which preserves a steep y)."}, {"term": "Equalized diastolic pressures", "def": "RA ≈ RV diastolic ≈ PCWP ≈ intrapericardial pressure, all elevated, because the effusion transmits a common compressive pressure."}, {"term": "Blunted/absent Kussmaul", "def": "Unlike constriction, RA pressure still falls (or does not rise) with inspiration in classic tamponade."}]}, {"type": "steps", "depth": 2, "label": "Confirming tamponade relief at pericardiocentesis", "items": ["Transduce the pericardial space AND the RA simultaneously before drainage — intrapericardial pressure is elevated and tracks RA pressure.", "Aspirate fluid incrementally, watching the intrapericardial pressure fall.", "Relief is confirmed when intrapericardial pressure falls toward zero/negative and SEPARATES from the RA pressure (the two tracings, previously superimposed, diverge).", "Reassess for UNMASKED constriction or a persistently elevated RA pressure — effusive-constrictive pericarditis shows a failure of RA pressure to normalize despite a now-low intrapericardial pressure.", "A rising cardiac output and resolving pulsus paradoxus confirm hemodynamic success."]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 1, "label": "Danger", "text": "Do NOT give aggressive diuretics or vasodilators in tamponade — a tamponade patient is preload-dependent, and dropping filling pressure can precipitate collapse. Cautious volume and pressor support are bridges; the definitive treatment is DRAINAGE. Positive-pressure ventilation and intubation can further impair filling and cause peri-induction arrest — drain first when feasible."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "label": "Fellowship pearl — effusive-constrictive pericarditis", "text": "If, after complete drainage, the intrapericardial pressure is normal but RA pressure remains elevated (classically failing to fall by ≥50% or to below ~10 mmHg) with a now-appearing steep y descent and dip-and-plateau, the visceral pericardium is constricting beneath the effusion — effusive-constrictive physiology. It behaves like constriction and may need pericardiectomy, not just drainage. This is why you transduce and reassess AFTER the tap, not just declare victory when fluid comes out."}, {"type": "p", "depth": 2, "text": "See the pericardial-disease module for the echocardiographic correlates — RA systolic collapse (sensitive), RV early-diastolic collapse (specific), a plethoric non-collapsing IVC, and >25–40% respirophasic mitral/tricuspid inflow variation that mirror the catheter-derived interdependence."}]}, {"id": "pah", "title": "RHC in Pulmonary Hypertension and Vasoreactivity Testing", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "RHC is mandatory to CONFIRM pulmonary arterial hypertension (Group 1) before committing a patient to PAH-specific therapy, because echo estimates are imprecise and misclassification is costly. The complete PH study measures RA, RV, PA, PCWP, cardiac output (thermodilution AND Fick), calculates PVR, and — in idiopathic/heritable/drug-induced PAH — performs acute vasoreactivity testing to identify the small responder group eligible for calcium-channel-blocker therapy."}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 2, "label": "Positive acute vasoreactivity (Sitbon criteria)", "entries": [{"term": "Definition of a responder", "def": "A fall in mPAP of ≥10 mmHg to an absolute mPAP ≤40 mmHg, with an unchanged or increased cardiac output."}, {"term": "Why it matters", "def": "Only acute responders (~10% of IPAH) should be trialed on high-dose calcium channel blockers; the majority who are non-responders need PAH-targeted drugs, and CCBs would be dangerous."}, {"term": "Where it does NOT apply", "def": "Vasoreactivity testing guides CCB use only in idiopathic/heritable/drug-induced PAH — not in connective-tissue-disease, portopulmonary, or Group 2/3/4 PH."}]}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "label": "Agents for acute vasoreactivity testing", "head": ["Agent | mechanism", "Dose", "Duration / route", "Key contraindication", "Adverse effects", "Monitoring"], "rows": [["Inhaled nitric oxide | NO donor, selective pulmonary vasodilator", "10–20 ppm", "~5 min, inhaled", "Left-heart failure with high wedge (risk of edema)", "Rebound PH on withdrawal, methemoglobinemia", "mPAP, CO, systemic BP"], ["IV epoprostenol | prostacyclin analog", "2 ng/kg/min, uptitrate by 2 q10–15 min", "IV infusion to target", "Severe systemic hypotension", "Flushing, headache, hypotension, nausea, jaw pain", "Continuous BP, mPAP, CO"], ["IV/inhaled adenosine | endogenous vasodilator", "50 mcg/kg/min, uptitrate", "IV, very short half-life", "High-grade AV block, sick sinus, bronchospasm", "Chest tightness, AV block, flushing, dyspnea", "ECG/rhythm, BP, mPAP"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 2, "label": "Danger", "text": "In pulmonary veno-occlusive disease and in Group 2 PH with a high wedge, potent pulmonary vasodilators can precipitate acute pulmonary edema by increasing flow into an obstructed venous bed. Confirm the wedge and consider the phenotype before challenging. Calcium channel blockers given to a NON-responder can cause fatal hemodynamic collapse — reactivity status must be documented before CCB therapy."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "label": "Fellowship framing — the fluid challenge and exercise RHC", "text": "A resting wedge in the gray zone (13–15 mmHg) in a patient with HFpEF risk factors may be provoked with 500 mL saline or supine exercise; a wedge rising to ≥18 (fluid) or ≥25 (exercise) reclassifies apparent precapillary PH as post-capillary. Getting this right changes the entire treatment pathway — targeted PAH drugs help Group 1 and harm decompensated Group 2."}, {"type": "linkout", "depth": 1, "text": "The Sitbon vasoreactivity criteria and the current hemodynamic definitions of PH derive from the primary PAH literature and consensus documents.", "url": "https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov", "label": "PubMed — acute vasoreactivity and PH hemodynamic definitions"}]}, {"id": "pitfalls", "title": "Artifacts, Pitfalls, and Quality Control", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "Most \"impossible\" hemodynamics are measurement errors, not exotic physiology. Before you build a diagnosis on a number, interrogate the tracing: is it damped or whipped, is the transducer level, are you reading end-expiration, and does the derived value pass a plausibility check against the others?"}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "label": "Common artifacts and fixes", "head": ["Artifact", "Appearance", "Fix"], "rows": [["Over-damping", "Rounded, low peaks, lost dicrotic notch", "Flush line, remove air/clot, check connections"], ["Under-damping (whip/fling)", "Exaggerated spikes, overshoot", "Add damping, remove excess tubing/stopcocks, avoid catheter whip"], ["Transducer mis-leveled", "Systematically high or low pressures", "Re-zero and re-level to the phlebostatic axis"], ["Reading mid-respiration", "Falsely low (spontaneous) or high (PPV) pressures", "Read at end-expiration — peak (spontaneous) or nadir (PPV)"], ["Over-wedge", "Wedge drifts up, loses a/v waves", "Deflate slightly, pull back; confirm arterialized sat"], ["Catheter whip (PA)", "Superimposed motion artifact on PA tracing", "Reposition; average over the cardiac cycle"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 1, "label": "Pearl", "text": "Run a plausibility loop on every study: PA diastolic should be near the wedge (if far apart, suspect precapillary disease OR an over-wedge); RV systolic should equal PA systolic (if not, think RVOT/pulmonic obstruction or catheter position); and the two independent cardiac outputs (Fick and thermodilution) should agree within ~15% (if not, one method is being fooled — TR, low output, or shunt). Numbers that do not cohere are a data-quality problem until proven otherwise."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "label": "Fellowship discipline", "text": "Record simultaneous, high-fidelity (micromanometer where available) tracings when the answer hinges on dynamics — constriction vs restriction, low-flow AS, giant v waves. Fluid-filled systems introduce phase lag and damping that blunt exactly the respiratory discordance and gradient timing you are trying to measure. When the stakes are pericardiectomy or valve replacement, the quality of the tracing is the diagnosis."}]}], "quiz": [{"stem": "A 61-year-old man with prior mediastinal radiation for lymphoma presents with progressive edema, ascites, and dyspnea. At catheterization, RA mean is 18 mmHg with prominent x and y descents, RVEDP is 19 mmHg, PCWP is 20 mmHg, and LVEDP is 21 mmHg. On inspiration, RA pressure fails to fall, and simultaneous RV and LV tracings show that the RV systolic pressure RISES while the LV systolic pressure FALLS. Which finding most specifically establishes the diagnosis?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Equalization of diastolic pressures within 5 mmHg"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Kussmaul sign (RA pressure failing to fall with inspiration)"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Respiratory discordance of RV and LV systolic pressures (ventricular interdependence)"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Prominent x and y descents on the RA tracing"}, {"key": "E", "text": "A dip-and-plateau contour on the ventricular tracing"}], "correct": "C", "explanation": "The picture is constrictive pericarditis (post-radiation). Diastolic equalization, prominent x/y descents, Kussmaul sign, and the dip-and-plateau all occur in constriction but also overlap substantially with restrictive cardiomyopathy. The single most SPECIFIC invasive discriminator is enhanced ventricular interdependence: because the rigid pericardium dissociates the chambers from intrathoracic pressure, inspiration augments RV filling and shifts the septum, so RV systolic pressure rises while LV systolic pressure falls — DISCORDANT peaks (quantified as a systolic area index >1.1). In restriction the ventricular systolic pressures move concordantly."}, {"stem": "A 48-year-old woman with a large pericardial effusion is hypotensive (BP 88/64) and tachycardic. During careful blood-pressure measurement, systolic pressure falls by 16 mmHg during quiet inspiration. Right-heart catheterization shows RA mean 16, RV diastolic 16, and PCWP 17 mmHg, with a prominent x descent and an attenuated y descent. Which mechanism best explains the blunted y descent?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Rapid, unimpeded early ventricular filling followed by an abrupt halt"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Elevated pericardial pressure impeding ventricular filling throughout diastole, preventing rapid early filling"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Severe tricuspid regurgitation ventricularizing the RA tracing"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Atrial fibrillation eliminating the a wave"}, {"key": "E", "text": "Complete heart block producing cannon a waves"}], "correct": "B", "explanation": "This is cardiac tamponade (pulsus paradoxus >10 mmHg, equalized elevated diastolic pressures). The y descent reflects rapid early-diastolic atrial emptying when the AV valve opens. In tamponade the effusion keeps intrapericardial (and therefore chamber) pressure elevated throughout diastole, so there is never an unimpeded early-filling phase — the y descent is blunted or absent, and the x descent dominates. Option A describes constriction, where early filling IS unimpeded and the y descent is steep."}, {"stem": "A 55-year-old man in cardiogenic shock after a large anterior MI has CI 1.7 L/min/m², PCWP 26 mmHg, SVR 1600 dynes·s·cm⁻⁵, and MAP 62 mmHg on no vasoactive support. A colleague suggests starting dopamine. Based on trial evidence, what is the most appropriate first-line vasopressor and why?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Dopamine, because it augments renal perfusion at low doses"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Norepinephrine, because dopamine caused more arrhythmias and higher mortality in the cardiogenic-shock subgroup of SOAP II"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Phenylephrine, because pure alpha-agonism best supports this patient"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Vasopressin monotherapy, because it avoids beta-adrenergic effects"}, {"key": "E", "text": "High-dose milrinone bolus, to rapidly augment contractility"}], "correct": "B", "explanation": "Norepinephrine is the preferred first-line vasopressor in cardiogenic shock. In the SOAP II trial, dopamine was associated with more arrhythmic events overall and higher mortality specifically in the cardiogenic-shock subgroup compared with norepinephrine. Pure alpha-agonism (phenylephrine) raises afterload without inotropy and can worsen an already low output. A milrinone BOLUS in a hypotensive patient risks profound, long-lasting hypotension. This patient is cold and wet — after restoring perfusion pressure, an inotrope (e.g., dobutamine or milrinone by infusion) and MCS consideration are appropriate."}, {"stem": "During a shunt evaluation, oxygen saturations are: SVC 62%, IVC 68%, RA 63%, RV 78%, PA 79%, systemic artery 96%. Which lesion is most consistent with these data?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Secundum atrial septal defect"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Ventricular septal defect"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Patent ductus arteriosus"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Right-to-left shunt across a patent foramen ovale"}, {"key": "E", "text": "No significant shunt"}], "correct": "B", "explanation": "The diagnostic step-up occurs from RA (63%) to RV (78%) — a 15% increase, well above the ≥5% threshold for a ventricular-level step-up — indicating oxygenated blood entering at the RV, i.e., a VSD. An ASD would show the step-up one level higher, from the great veins (mixed venous ~ (3×SVC + IVC)/4 ≈ 63.5%) to the RA (≥7% threshold). A PDA would step up from RV to PA. The systemic saturation of 96% and the location of the step-up make a VSD the answer; there is no desaturation to suggest a right-to-left shunt."}, {"stem": "A 70-year-old woman with dyspnea has an echo suggesting severe aortic stenosis, but her cardiac output is low (CI 1.6 L/min/m²) and the invasive mean gradient is only 22 mmHg. The calculated Gorlin valve area is 0.8 cm². What is the best next step to determine whether the stenosis is truly severe?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Proceed directly to valve replacement based on the calculated area"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Perform low-dose dobutamine challenge to assess flow reserve and change in gradient/area"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Give aggressive diuresis and recheck the gradient"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Use the femoral sheath pressure as the aortic pressure to recompute the gradient"}, {"key": "E", "text": "Start nitroprusside to reduce afterload and repeat the Gorlin calculation"}], "correct": "B", "explanation": "This is low-flow, low-gradient AS. The Gorlin equation is flow-dependent, so at low cardiac output the calculated area is falsely small even when the valve is not critically stenotic (pseudo-severe AS). A low-dose dobutamine challenge augments flow: in TRUE-severe AS the area stays fixed and the gradient rises, whereas in PSEUDO-severe AS the area increases as flow rises and the gradient stays modest. Acting on the resting Gorlin area alone (A) risks operating on pseudo-severe disease. Using the damped, amplified femoral sheath pressure (D) distorts the gradient and is never a substitute for a true LV-to-aortic measurement."}, {"stem": "A 34-year-old woman with idiopathic pulmonary arterial hypertension undergoes acute vasoreactivity testing with inhaled nitric oxide. Her mPAP falls from 55 to 42 mmHg, and cardiac output rises slightly. According to accepted criteria, how should this result be interpreted and what does it imply for therapy?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Positive responder — start high-dose calcium channel blocker therapy"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Negative responder — do not use calcium channel blockers; use PAH-targeted therapy"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Positive responder — start an endothelin receptor antagonist"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Indeterminate — the test must be repeated with epoprostenol"}, {"key": "E", "text": "Positive responder because cardiac output increased, regardless of the mPAP value"}], "correct": "B", "explanation": "The Sitbon criteria for a positive acute vasoreactivity response require a fall in mPAP of ≥10 mmHg TO AN ABSOLUTE mPAP ≤40 mmHg with preserved or increased cardiac output. Here the mPAP fell 13 mmHg (meets the ≥10 drop) but only reached 42 mmHg, NOT ≤40 — so the patient is a NON-responder. Non-responders should NOT receive calcium channel blockers (which can cause hemodynamic collapse) and instead need PAH-specific therapy. Only the roughly 10% of IPAH patients who meet both parts of the criterion are candidates for a CCB trial."}], "references": ["ESC/ERS 2022 Guidelines for the Diagnosis and Treatment of Pulmonary Hypertension (Humbert et al.)", "2020 ACC/AHA Guideline for the Management of Patients With Valvular Heart Disease (Otto et al.)", "2015 ESC Guidelines for the Diagnosis and Management of Pericardial Diseases (Adler et al.)", "Forrester JS et al. Medical therapy of acute myocardial infarction by application of hemodynamic subsets (NEJM 1976)", "ESCAPE Trial — Evaluation Study of Congestive Heart Failure and Pulmonary Artery Catheterization Effectiveness (JAMA 2005)", "SOAP II Trial — De Backer et al. Comparison of dopamine and norepinephrine in the treatment of shock (NEJM 2010)", "SCAI Clinical Expert Consensus Statement on the Classification of Cardiogenic Shock (Baran et al., 2019; SCAI SHOCK Stage Classification Expert Consensus update, 2022)", "Gorlin R, Gorlin SG. Hydraulic formula for calculation of the area of the stenotic mitral valve, other cardiac valves, and central circulatory shunts (Am Heart J 1951)"]};
